76561198052919524,Recommended,283960,31763183,Posted: 14 May,all,BeatleNumber9,"It was nice experiencing this little gem from my childhood again.If you like point-and-click adventure games, especially the kind of surreal ones, where practically anything and everything is clickable, get this game! I was really worried that this game wouldn't hold up as well, playing it as an adult, but I can say that I still enjoyed the humor and the characters. Some of the animations might be a little dated, but what do you expect it's from 1996 (God I'm old). I had so much fun, I might just check out the other Pajama Sam games that are now available, as this was the only one I played as a kid.Pajama Sam: NNHWIDO has basically an Alice in Wonderland-type story. Pajama Sam gets transported to the Land of Darkness through his bedroom closet, and goes on a journey through the land to vanquish Darkness, the character whom the land is so aptly named after. It's pretty simple, but that's really all it needs to be. The real focus is the humor and characters and both are just filled with so much charm. There's the boat who's afraid of water, the old mine car who's become rusted to the tracks, and the (literal) wishing well, who makes wishes when you throw him a penny. Yeah, this game's pretty weird, but that's what makes it so fun.Like I said earlier practically everything in the game reacts to you clicking it, usually in more ways than one. One item may have multiple comedic reactions to you clicking on it. Seriously try and click everything in this game, even stuff in the background that just looks like it's part of the environment. I discovered some clickables playing the game now, that I never found as a kid.This game also has surprising replay value. There will often be different parts of the environment generated in future playthroughs that replace some from previous playthroughs. These add more to the game; more jokes, more story, more characters.Even if you aren't a kid check this game out, it's still pretty entertaining as an adult, plus it's fairly priced. It kind of reminds me of watching some of the old Cartoon Network shows I grew up with as a kid, it may be kind of old, but it's still fun. Check it out if you've got 7 dollars to spare."
76561198089907009,Recommended,283960,10216724,"Posted: 24 May, 2014",all,ConmanWolf,"Ages ago, a game about a young boy with a skin disease and odd hair growth set out to fight Darkness.Pajama Sam is actually quite simple. You may need to spend some times figuring out the controls, but it's easy once you get the hang of it. The game isn't that long either. You can get through it in about 2 hours or less without even trying that hard. But, Pajama Sam has an old school sense of humor. (Read: Actually funny.) Unlike other kid games or movies that are just dumb, Pajama Sam can be actually funny, with a great attention to detail.Even though the game graphics are WAY out of date and you can see the pixels, it still has an odd charm.Pajama Sam is the only game in which you can lead a carrot rebellion, answer questions about World Leaders, and beat a toaster in a game of Tic-Tac-Toe.I recommend it if you can spend some money on a VERY short game. And if you want more milleages out of it? Maybe you should livestream it. I'm sure a lot of people will have a good laugh."
